data.title: 'I was not derailed'

data.text:
HYANNIS — When Glenn J. Martin of West Yarmouth started the nursing program at Cape Cod Community College five years ago at age 38, he was nervous about washing out.

And he did.

Trying to juggle work with a demanding course load and his responsibilities as a husband and father, Martin flunked a semester.

“I felt defeated. I was demoralized,” Martin told more than 500 graduates of the college's degree and certificate programs during a commencement ceremony Thursday afternoon at the Cape Cod Melody Tent.

“I was not derailed,” Martin said.

Instead he campaigned to be readmitted to the competitive nursing program and pressed onward, graduating Thursday with an associate in science degree from the nursing program as a member of the Phi Theta Kappa Honor Society.

If he had given up on the nursing program, he would have been stuck in a career where he felt stultified and depressed, Martin said.

“I wanted to quit. It would have been so easy to walk away. But I didn’t,” said Martin, who received a standing ovation after giving the student commencement talk.

Failure tests commitment, but facing it yields great rewards — a degree, a better job, a brighter future, Martin said.

“Failure is everywhere,” Martin said. “We’ve all come back in spite of it.”

Look for support from those who want to help, Martin said.

He thanked his wife and children as well as the professors and librarians at the college and the staff of the the financial aid, advising, tutoring and O’Neill centers for their help the way.

Cape Cod Community College alumnus Tim Kelley, Boston meteorologist with NECN/NBC10, gave the commencement address and told graduates it was a waitress at the Ebb Tide Restaurant who convinced him to go on to college.

Being an active, outdoors-oriented child who had hated school since day one, Kelley said he was surprised to find he really enjoyed community college.

And he said he was ecstatic to learn he could go to Lyndon State College in Vermont and earn a degree in the one subject that had fascinated him since childhood: meteorology.

Kelley joked that “an ‘ologist’ gets paid to do what he or she likes to do. I don’t call work work. I call work play.”

Cape Cod Community College President John Cox told the graduates not to be afraid of obstacles.

“There are many who want to see you succeed in your own special way,” he said.

— Follow Cynthia McCormick on Twitter: @CmccormickCCT.
